  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Carpal tunnel syndrome (CTS) is the most common peripheral nerve entrapment. Diagnosis is
      based on symptoms, clinical findings and electrophysiological examination. Several
      conservative and surgical treatment options have been described.

      Studies of surgical versus conservative treatment in mild carpal tunnel syndrome have not
      been done and it is still unclear whether or not surgical treatment is better than
      conservative treatment.

      The aim of this study is to research has surgery better outcome in mild CTS than conservative
      treatment. Patient satisfactory, clinical and electrophysiologic outcomes, direct and
      indirect costs will be evaluated.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
